<TEXT>
california attorney general john van de 
kamp formally launched his campaign for governor sunday in rival 
dianne feinsteins political backyard with a scathing attack on her 
record as mayor of san francisco 
van de kamp began with a rally at the mission high school boys 
gymnasium in the heart of the city where feinstein served nine 
years as mayor and ripped into feinsteins fiscal management and 
her record on civil rights insurance the environment and womens 
issues 
dianne feinsteins budget mismanagement turned the city by the 
bay into the city that could not pay van de kamp said accusing 
her of being evasive on how she would balance the state budget 
van de kamp describing himself as a candidate who is going to 
change california with environmental political ethics and drug 
reforms 
a spokesman for feinstein called van de kamps attack a sign of 
desperation in the wake of the most recent poll on the june 5 
democratic primary in which the former mayor pulled ahead of the 
attorney general 
the kickoff announcement is only a formality since van de kamp 
like feinstein has been actively campaigning for a year and leads 
feinstein in fund raising by 46 million to 23 million 
the winner of their june 5 primary will face the expected 
republican nominee us sen pete wilson in november incumbent 
gov george deukmejian a republican is retiring 
van de kamps campaign for governor is tied closely to three 
ballot initiatives he is sponsoring on the environment legislative 
ethics and crime the content of van de kamps initiatives has also 
stirred controversy part of his crime initiative duplicates an 
initiative sponsored by wilson except for deletion of privacy 
language which van de kamp claims could undermine a womans right 
to abortion and his political ethics initiative contains a 
controversial limit on the terms of legislators 
the ethics proposal has strained van de kamps relations with 
legislative leaders of his own party not only because of the 
proposed limit on their terms but especially because of a 
supporting article van de kamp wrote in which he said of the 
legislature if we want clean government its time to drain the 
swamp 
van de kamp 54 is a member of the wealthy pasadena family 
which formerly owned the frozen food company and the southern 
california bakery chain which still carry the family name 
before his election as attorney general in 1982 van de kamp 
served seven years as los angeles county district attorney five 
years as federal public defender and two years as assistant federal 
public defender in los angeles 
</TEXT>
