president bush said sunday that whoever 
wins the election in nicaragua will find a better climate 
with the united states so long as the balloting is certified as 
free and fair and the resulting government maintains a democratic 
system 
fair elections would be very very helpful even if the 
sandinista government wins sundays balloting bush said 
the united states has supported political and military 
opposition to the daniel ortegas sandinista government and bush 
said he thought victory by the opposition would be for the best 
meanwhile nbc news reported the bush administration already has 
had direct highlevel contacts with the sandinistas making it 
clear the united states would open the door to normalizing 
relations if the sandinistas fulfilled certain conditions 
nbc said both sides agreed to basic terms including 
certifiably free and fair elections cessation of arms export by 
the sandinistas to leftist guerrillas in the region and increased 
democracy in nicaragua 
according to the report bush would resume official highlevel 
talks allow the current us economic embargo to expire and resume 
normal diplomatic relations 
asked about high level talks between us and nicaraguan 
officials bush attending an official dinner with the nations 
governors sunday night said better not be i dont believe 
it 
asked about former president carters criticism that the us 
role in nicaragua has not been constructive in recent yeras bush 
said only interesting 
on another topic bush said his upcoming meeting in palm springs 
fla with japanese prime minister toshiki kaifu is very 
improtant now that hes solidfied his position the united 
states as fascinated as we are with changes in europe and even 
south america does not want to send a signal to our friends in the 
pacific that we are neglecting them 
in addition bernard aronson assistant secretary of state for 
latin american affairs denied direct contacts between highlevel 
us and nicaraguan officials 
he said that while us embassy officials in managua talk daily 
to the sandinista government the only contact of the level nbc 
reported was made last novemeber when the organization of the 
american states sponsored talks in washington between the contras 
and sandinistas aimed at reinstating a ceasefire in the contra 
war 
the notion theres been some kind of negotiations or quid pro 
quo dealing with postelection agreements is just total 
fantasy aronson said in a telephone interview 
he noted that secretary of state james a baker iii has publicly 
stated that in the event of a sandinista victory the united states 
would consider normalizing relations if the election is fair the 
sandinistas stop exporting revolution and show commitment to 
democratic principles 
aronson speculated that the managua government is falsely 
telling reporters it has made agreements with highlevel us 
officials to bolster ortegas election bid 
this is just an effort to make the sandinistas look like 
winners he said 
despite his difficulties with the sandinista government bush 
earlier said let me say this if these elections are certifiably 
free and fair whoever wins the election will find a better climate 
in which to improve relations with nicaragua 
asked earlier what the us policy would be if ortega the 
sandinista leader was kept in power in the historic nicaraguan 
voting bush said he would not accept the premise of the questions 
he also refused to talk extensively about nicaragua for fear it 
might influence the balloting then under way 
but he said the government that wins the elections must prove it 
supports democracratic principles there has got to be a period 
of establishing bona fides he said 
while elections are important what follows in terms of 
freedom of the press freedom of institutions there freedom to 
protest freedom to speak their mind is also crucial he said 
i would love to see nicaragua living peacefully within its own 
borders not trying to subvert its neighbors and giving its people 
a shot at democracy he said 
once all that was sorted out i can guarantee you that there 
would be better relations with nicaragua he said 
