<TEXT>
malcolm forbes was mourned by friends and 
competitors alike as a maverick business superstar whose knack for 
extravagant spending and the active life made all our lives a 
little more colorful 
he was the quintessential american optimistic buoyant and 
lots of fun he was a very good friend and ill miss him said 
henry kissinger former secretary of state 
forbes died of a heart attack in his sleep saturday in his new 
jersey home said william donald garson director of corporate 
communications for new yorkbased forbes inc 
mayor david dinkins praised forbes as one of new york citys 
most creative and vibrant characters 
in the finest tradition of american publishing he could tweak 
the greatest figures of business and finance and then entertain 
them with a grand party dinkins said through a spokesman he 
celebrated his good fortune on a scale that only the world could 
accommodate 
his business competitors heaped equal amounts of praise on the 
tychoon who was often seen in the company of actress elizabeth 
taylor 
he was a hell of a competitor and a promotional genius said 
stephen shepard editor in chief of business week magazine he 
gave the magazine a personality an image of wealth extravagance 
and strong opinion he was something of a maverick and so was his 
magazine 
marshall loeb managing editor of fortune magazine called 
forbes one of the most effective salespeople in the world he 
was a worthy competitor certainly tough charming very very 
effective 
warren h phillips chairman and chief executive of dow jones amp 
co which publishes the wall street journal said he was unique 
and larger than life as a journalist entrepreneur and human being 
never afraid to defy convention to chart new paths of flair 
and adventure whether in his publications or his personal life 
in a characteristic flaunting of wealth forbes last year spent 
2 million to celebrate his 70th birthday in morocco one of the 
guests at the party was his longtime friend opera star beverly 
sills who sang happy birthday to the eccentric businessman 
he was a real free spirit sills said saturday he had 
such a joy of life i think he would have had it if he had been a 
poor man 
sills said she first met forbes many many years ago when he 
wrote me a fan letter and invited me on his boat 
another guest at the birthday bash chrysler corp chairman lee 
iacocca said forbes lived life to its fullest and in doing so 
made all of our lives a little more colorful 
owners of both new york baseball teams extolled forbes flair 
and his business acumen 
fred wilpon an owner of the new york mets and a realestate 
developer in new york said through a spokesman that forbes had 
scaled the heights of business journalism and left an indelible 
positive mark on our society 
and george steinbrenner principal owner of the new york 
yankees said through a spokesman he made his mark through 
integrity a toughness and wonderful sense of humor 
forbes was the babe ruth of business publishing 
steinbrenner said 
