<TEXT>
its the time of year when winds over the south 
china sea blow north so hong kong is bracing for tens of thousands 
of vietnamese expected to set sail on the treacherous journey to 
its already overcrowded shores 
more than 35000 vietnamese swamped the british colony seeking 
asylum in 1989 if a similar wave of boat people arrives this year 
were going to be in trouble said mike hanson who coordinates 
government policy on boat people in hong kong 
about 55000 vietnamese already are languishing in hong kongs 
cramped prisonlike camps some will be resettled overseas as 
refugees but most will be deported as illegal immigrants because 
they cannot prove persecution back home 
on sunday local newspapers reported that a vietnamese refugee 
30yearold nguyen ho challenged the screening policy and appeals 
procedure by filing a lawsuit in the high court of hong kong on 
saturday government radio earlier said six refugees challenged the 
screening but it did not elaborate 
the new yorkbased lawyers committee for human rights said it 
helped prepare the lawsuit filed saturday and that more such action 
was forthcoming no court dates were given 
the refugee screening procedure that hong kong has used since 
june of 1988 is cursory and filled with potential for error the 
group said in a statement interviewers seem intent on 
establishing solely economic reasons for departure from vietnam 
even some people who have endured harsh reeducation programs or 
forced labor in vietnam have been rejected 
it will only take a few thousand more boat people to fill hong 
kongs existing camps to capacity then the government faces bleak 
options 
local lawmakers angered by the financial burden created by the 
boat people have delayed approval of a proposed 30 million 
detention center on a remote outlying island 
lacking new facilities hanson said the governments contingency 
plan calls for squeezing more vietnamese into the existing camps 
he conceded this would likely exacerbate tension in the camps 
where factional fighting is common and a handful of boat people 
facing repatriation have attempted suicide police in riot gear 
already have had to fire tear gas on several occasions to quell 
clashes 
other steps the government might have to take include placing 
new arrivals on ferries moored in the harbor which was done at the 
height of last years influx and erecting makeshift camps of 
little more than barbed wire enclosing flat space said a western 
diplomat who has been following developments 
the real crunch comes in july when youve run out of 
everything available and still they are coming said the 
diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity 
so far the government has resisted calls to push arriving boat 
people back out to sea but community pressure to take such action 
is sure to increase if this years influx is heavy 
it is impossible to estimate how many additional boat people 
will show up during the spring sailing season in hong kong a tiny 
territory on the south china coast about 500 miles northeast of the 
vietnamese port city of haiphong 
security secretary geoffrey barnes said he was encouraged that 
only 244 boat people had arrived this year through feb 22 a 45 
percent decline from the same period last year only eight of the 
1990 arrivals had sailed from northern vietnam the region from 
which most of last years boat people set sail 
barnes said the figures were too small to be regarded as 
significant but he attributed the decline in part to vietnamese 
efforts to prevent people from setting sail 
vietnamese officials in haiphong city and the northern province 
of quang ninh told the associated press in january of intensified 
efforts to apprehend organizers of sailing journeys to hong kong 
and to increase security along the coast 
they also have launched a media propaganda campaign to explain 
the tough living condition in the hong kong camps 
i think that the number of people that are going to leave 
vietnam will be limited to the minimum said hoang ngoc tri a 
haiphong official in charge of receiving repatriated boat people 
its very difficult to predict a figure but we want to stop 
it immediately absolutely all we can do is try our best he 
said 
hanson said one worrying development is that many of the 
vietnamese who have arrived in hong kong this year first traveled 
to china by land before setting sail the open border makes the 
trip very easy and very cheap he said 
he believes a key to keeping the influx to a minimum lies with 
continued repatriation of boat people against their will 
the hong kong government adopted a tough policy in june 1988 
under which boat people are considered illegal immigrants subject 
to repatriation unless they can show a wellfounded fear of 
persecution in their homeland 
an initial group of 51 boat people denied refugee status were 
sent home against their will in december although hanson believes 
the move had a deterrent effect no more vietnamese have been 
forced back since largely because of us demands they be given 
until next year to consider going home voluntarily 
the failure to get an international consensus on when to resume 
deportations has been distinctly unhelpful hanson said 
hanson believes that because washington delayed the deportation 
program it has a responsibility to help bear the cost of housing 
the boat people 
</TEXT>
