houphouetboigny called a national dialogue in september and told 
delegates no holds were barred 
it brought at least one demand he could not stomach again from 
the university lecturers union union president marcel ette urged 
creation of a multiparty democracy 
the president responded that there would be no multiparty 
democracy in ivory coast at least not in his lifetime as other 
african dictators have done he argued that a multiparty system 
would endanger national unity in a country still beset by tribal 
rivalries 
the ivory coast constitution allows political opposition but 
things start happening if you try to insist on your rights 
gbagbo said in an interview you and your friends get arrested 
your bank account gets frozen suddenly business isnt good 
houphouetboigny vigorously encouraged agricultural production 
of the cash crops pushed by western institutions in the 1960s and 
1970s 
while most of black africa became net food importers following 
independence from european colonial powers his efforts spurred 
ivorian farmers to record production 
last year amid a continuing slump in commodity prices ivory 
coast produced a record 820000 tons of cocoa nine times what it 
produced in 1960 and nearly a third of world production it is the 
worlds biggest cocoa producer 
but cocoa prices were slashed to half those of 1985 in october 
houphouetboigny was forced to abandon his promise to support 
prices for farmers and he cut promised producer prices for cocoa 
and coffee in half 
critics like gbagbo say the president is too old and set in his 
ways to look to industrialization and other routes to revive the 
economy 
but houphouetboigny looks more like a man in his 70s and 
appears alert astute and far from ready to retire 
the old regime is dying but its dying badly gbagbo 
complained 
its dying throes will come because ivorians are being hit where 
it hurts most in their pockets he said 
when wealthy ivorians go to the bank to cash a 17500 check 
the liquidity crisis forces the banks to tell them to make the 
check out for 88 he said 
a government clerk feeling the pinch of a pay cut expressed it 
another way last year i gave my son a few francs for lunch and 
he could have a hot stew and grilled bananas the same money today 
buys only the bananas and i dont have the extra money to buy him 
the stew 
