<TEXT>
free speech advocates say access to the public 
soapbox is at stake monday in a case before the us supreme court 
involving two lyndon larouche followers who tried to solicit 
support on a post office sidewalk 
the courts decision will either broaden access to government 
property for the purpose of free speech or further restrict what 
constitutes a public forum 
the case will also allow the court to clarify conflicting 
rulings from federal appeals courts on the governments ban on 
soliciting on postal service property 
groups such as the hare krishnas conservative christians the 
aflcio and newspapers have filed friendofthecourt briefs urging 
that free speech rights be expanded 
the public forum doctrine is for the little person said 
attorney jay sekulow missionaries and evangelicals cannot afford 
fullpage newspaper ads they can afford a sidewalk to talk to 
people about the gospel 
sekulow represents marsha kokinda and kevin pearl larouche 
volunteers who were convicted of violating a regulation against 
soliciting electioneering collecting debts vending and 
advertising on postal service property 
larouche a political extremist and sometime presidential 
candidate is serving a 15year prison term for his 1988 conviction 
on fraud and conspiracy charges prosecutors accused him of 
conspiring to accept millions of dollars in loans from political 
supporters he had no intention of repaying 
courts have wrestled with a number of cases in recent years 
seeking to define a public forum where speech cannot be 
unreasonably restricted judges have been asked to decide for 
example whether taxpayerfinanced airline terminals or private 
shopping malls can bar people from handing out leaflets or asking 
for contributions 
kokinda and pearl chose as their soapbox a narrow strip of 
sidewalk leading between the parking lot and the doors of the tiny 
post office on a busy highway in this washington suburb they were 
arrested in 1986 after they refused to stop soliciting 
contributions and distributing literature from a table 
kokinda was fined 50 and sentenced to 10 days in jail pearl 
was fined 100 their convictions were thrown out by the 4th us 
circuit court of appeals in 1989 
the supreme court will hear arguments monday and is expected to 
issue a decision by july 
in appealing to the high court the government argues that there 
is a difference between a city sidewalk and one located entirely on 
postal service property it also argues that picketing handing out 
pamphlets and soliciting interfere with postal business and a 
justice department attorney will argue monday that free speech is 
limited to some extent on all government property 
the 4th circuit ruling is binding in maryland north carolina 
south carolina virginia and west virginia 
but two other appeals courts have upheld the ban on soliciting 
on post office property so there is no nationwide standard for the 
postal service to follow 
david liberman an attorney for the international society of 
krishna consciousness said the postal service is isolating its 
property from other government buildings that are considered public 
where do you find the people these days a suburban post 
office is where you find the people if this is not a forum then 
the government can exclude everything from that place he said 
