east german premier hans modrow agreed sunday 
to lead his party in march 18 elections giving the embattled 
communists a last chance at political survival 
according to recent opinion polls modrow remains the most 
popular politician in east germany despitehis affiliation with a 
party that has been disgraced and stripped of most of its former 
authority 
the leftist social democratic party is expected to poll a 
majority of votes in east germanys firstever free elections 
followed by the more conservative christian democrats 
but modrows decision to stay with his party could boost the 
communists chances of retaining at least a minor role in the next 
leadership 
modrow told the 530 delegates at an east berlin convention of 
his party for democratic socialism that he would lead it in the 
march vote although it wasnt easy to make up his mind the 
official adn news agency said 
the 62yearold politician had been waffling over the leadership 
issue for several days he is apparently reluctant to become a 
scapegoat for four decades of communist economic mismanagement 
which the bonn government claims has brought east germany to the 
brink of ruin 
but modrow a member of the ruling politburo from 1958 until the 
communist party disbanded that body and changed its name last 
december enjoys widespread support as a reformer and is the 
partys most likely votegetter 
for all the things i tried to do for a policy of reform in 
1989 and maybe even earlier i now know very well that it wasnt 
enough adn quoted modrow as saying 
all leading east german parties have ruled out building 
coalition governments with the communists 
