terribly important player for a meaningful part of the legal 
community in new york 
roger meltzer a partner with cahill gordon amp reindel which has 
represented drexel for 10 years conceded that drexels demise 
would hurt but added that the firm has a substantial and diverse 
client base the firm reportedly did about 10 million in drexel 
business a year cahill gordon said in court papers it is owed 21 
million 
this firm is not based on the financial health of one 
client meltzer asserted never has been never will be 
drexel said it spent 75 million on legal fees associated with 
its criminal and civil troubles last year when it pleaded guilty 
to six felonies and paid 500 million of 650 million owed in 
government penalties a mountain of litigation spawned by drexels 
behavior still is outstanding 
the governments investigation made drexel a legal cottage 
industry and its collapse leaves bills scattered from coast to 
coast lawyers for current and former employees said they expect to 
press for some of the millions owed at least one major new york 
firm has its bankruptcy lawyer examining the issue 
everybody would like to be paid said gerald lefcourt who 
represents bruce newberg a former drexel junk bond trader who has 
been convicted of securities fraud and was indicted along with 
milken i dont know whether we will or wont 
with drexel busy disposing of billions of dollars in securities 
holdings and addressing the thorny matter of having paid 260 
million in bonuses as its financial fortunes sank paying more 
money to lawyers hasnt been a priority 
theyre pretty busy i havent been able to get through 
said daniel bookin a san francisco attorney for lisa jones a 
former drexel bond trading assistant who is appealing her 
conviction for lying to a federal grand jury 
drexel spokesman steven anreder said backedup legal bills 
will be dealt with in due course but he didnt know how much 
was owed anreder said drexel had for the time stopped paying for 
individuals new legal expenses 
drexel reportedly owes milken attorneys mostly at the new york 
firm paul weiss rifkind wharton amp garrison back pay for three 
or four months consistent with what other firms representing 
drexel people claim is due 
the firm capped spending by milkens criminal defense team last 
summer after it had rung up gargantuan legal bills to pay for two 
fulltime lawyers who reportedly bill out at 450 an hour and a 
football team worth of associates 
drexel also anted up for milkens defense against civil lawsuits 
claiming his actions as head of drexels highyield bond division 
defrauded investors 
the arrangement was unusual to begin with drexel paying to 
defend the man who allegedly masterminded the crimes to which the 
firm admitted a spokesman for milken said the indicted financier 
would foot his own expenses from now on 
for milken who made 550 million in 1987 that wont be a 
problem other clients such as lisa jones depended on drexel to 
pay the bills but bookin her attorney said his firm will not 
abandon lisa jones 
no attorneys have as yet filed claims against the firm or its 
parent drexel burnham lambert group inc which filed for chapter 
11 bankruptcy protection on feb 13 seeking to get the back pay 
the dismantling of drexel also has created legal complications 
for civil claimants who say they were defrauded by drexel trading 
in the past and that means more work for lawyers 
drexels liquidation doesnt absolve the firm from civil 
wrongdoing and lawyers said they will seek to recover assets from 
the firm if their claims are upheld they also said they will try 
to find out whether drexel wrongfully drained away assets 
including the 1989 bonuses 
they still have all their legal liabilities and are not 
protected by a bankruptcy case said dan mogan a san diego 
attorney representing shareholders of companies with which drexel 
had dealings 
